Regarding Streams:

know the difference btw 
.map() → before collect
toMap() → creates map
mapping() → used inside groupingBy
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 Core Difference (Simple View)
Concept	Works On	Purpose
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
.map()	Stream elements	Transform each element
Collectors.toMap()	Stream → Map	Build a Map
Collectors.mapping()	Inside collectors	Transform values during grouping
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔷 1. .map() → Transformation (Stream Level)

👉 Works on each element in the stream

Example:
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("a", "bb", "ccc");

List<Integer> lengths = list.stream()
        .map(s -> s.length())
        .collect(Collectors.toList());

✔ Converts String → Integer

👉 Output:
[1, 2, 3]
💡 Key Point
Used before collect
Changes stream data type
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔷 2. Collectors.toMap() → Build Map

👉 Converts stream into a Map<K, V>

Example:
List<String> list = Arrays.asList("a", "bb", "ccc");

Map<String, Integer> map = list.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.toMap(
                s -> s,          // key
                s -> s.length()  // value
        ));

👉 Output:

{a=1, bb=2, ccc=3}
⚠️ Important
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Handles duplicates using merge function:

Collectors.toMap(
    keyMapper,
    valueMapper,
    (oldVal, newVal) -> oldVal
)
💡 Key Point
Terminal operation (collect)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Creates Map
🔷 3. Collectors.mapping() → Transform INSIDE grouping

👉 Used only inside another collector (like groupingBy)

Example:
Map<Integer, List<String>> result =
    list.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
            String::length,
            Collectors.mapping(
                s -> s.toUpperCase(),
                Collectors.toList()
            )
        ));

👉 Output:

{1=[A], 2=[BB], 3=[CCC]}
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
💡 What’s happening?
First groups by length
Then modifies values (uppercase)
❌ Your Statement (Fixing)

Collectors.mapping() modifies only the values inside grouping, not keys and not the original map

🔥 Real Comparison Example
Without mapping()
Map<Integer, List<String>> map =
    list.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(String::length));
With mapping()
Map<Integer, List<Integer>> map =
    list.stream()
        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
            String::length,
            Collectors.mapping(
                s -> s.length(),
                Collectors.toList()
            )
        ));
🎯 Interview One-Liner Answers
.map() → transforms elements in stream
toMap() → converts stream into map
mapping() → transforms values inside grouping collector
