1. max() and min()
✅ Method Signature
Optional<T> max(Comparator<? super T> comparator)
Optional<T> min(Comparator<? super T> comparator)
🔹 Parameters

👉 Both require a Comparator

Example:

Comparator<Integer> comp = (a, b) -> a - b;
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Or shortcut:

Comparator.naturalOrder()
Comparator.reverseOrder()
🔹 Return Type
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
👉 Optional<T>

Why Optional?

Stream may be empty
Avoids NullPointerException
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔹 Example
List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(10, 20, 5, 30);

Optional<Integer> max = list.stream()
        .max(Integer::compareTo);

Optional<Integer> min = list.stream()
        .min(Integer::compareTo);

System.out.println(max.get()); // 30
System.out.println(min.get()); // 5
🔥 Important Interview Point
max.get(); // ❌ Risky if empty

Safer:
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
max.orElse(0);
🔷 For Objects
class Employee {
    String name;
    int salary;
}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Employee maxEmp = list.stream()
        .max(Comparator.comparing(Employee::getSalary))
        .orElse(null);
🔷 2. average()
✅ Method Signature
OptionalDouble average()
🔹 Where available?
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
👉 Only on primitive streams

IntStream
LongStream
DoubleStream
🔹 Parameters

👉 ❌ No parameters

🔹 Return Type
👉 OptionalDouble
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔹 Example
int[] arr = {10, 20, 30};

OptionalDouble avg = Arrays.stream(arr)
        .average();

System.out.println(avg.getAsDouble()); // 20.0
🔥 Important
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
You cannot do this directly:

List<Integer> list = Arrays.asList(10, 20, 30);
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
// ❌ ERROR
list.stream().average();
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
✅ Correct Way
double avg = list.stream()
        .mapToInt(Integer::intValue)
        .average()
        .orElse(0);
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔷 Summary Table
Method	      Parameter         	Return Type	Works On
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
max()       	Comparator     	Optional<T>	Object streams
min()	       Comparator 	     Optional<T>	Object streams
average()	      None	         OptionalDouble	Primitive streams
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 Shortcut Examples
✔ Max
list.stream().max(Integer::compareTo);
✔ Min
list.stream().min(Integer::compareTo);
✔ Average
list.stream().mapToInt(i -> i).average();
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🚀 Key Interview Traps
❌ Trap 1
list.stream().average(); // WRONG
❌ Trap 2
max(); // without comparator → ERROR
❌ Trap 3

Forgetting Optional handling
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🎯 One-Line Memory Trick
max/min → need Comparator
average → need primitive stream
All return Optional
